---
description: Angular house conventions - apply when editing Angular component/service/directive/etc. files.
globs: "**/*.component.ts,**/*.service.ts,**/*.directive.ts,**/*.pipe.ts,**/*.guard.ts,**/*.resolver.ts,**/*.interceptor.ts,**/*.component.html"
alwaysApply: false
---

When creating or editing Angular files (`*.component.ts`, `*.service.ts`, `*.directive.ts`,
`*.pipe.ts`, `*.guard.ts`, `*.resolver.ts`, `*.interceptor.ts`,
`*.component.html`), follow the `angular-conventions` skill under `.cursor/skills/`:
signals, standalone components, OnPush, reactive forms, accessibility. On the `.ts` files the
TypeScript baseline (`typescript-conventions.mdc`) also auto-attaches, so both compose.

If the `angular-conventions` skill is not loaded, hold the line on the highest-value rules:
standalone components with `inject()` over constructor injection, signals over manual
subscriptions, and `OnPush` change detection. Target the Angular 17+ house floor, reaching for the newest idioms the workspace ships.

This is guidance, auto-attached by glob (not a hard block). Bare `.html` stays ungated
(Angular template vs static page is ambiguous).
